The Ogun State Judicial Panel of Investigation set up to investigate complaints and petitions of victims of police brutality and abuse of human rights by security operatives, will begin sitting on Thursday, November 5. This was disclosed by the Chairman of the Panel, Justice Solomon Olugbemi (retd), shortly after a meeting of the Panel, that the panel would be sitting on Mondays, Wednesdays and Thursdays at 11.00 am each day, at the Magistrate Court 1, Isabo, Abeokuta. ALSO READ: How is gum disease linked to inflammation, heart disease, cancer? Justice Olugbemi said the Panel had received 20 petitions within two weeks of its inauguration while promising to that the sittings will be transparent and open. He enjoined journalists and media stations to cover the sittings, saying that the Panel will evaluate the evidence presented and circumstantial details towards drawing conclusions as to the validity of the complaints while recommending compensation and other remedies where appropriate. The retired judge called on members of the public who have complaints to send their petitions to the Secretary of the Panel or send online to endsarsjudicialpanel@ogunstate.gov.ng. YOU SHOULD NOT MISS THESE HEADLINES FROM NIGERIAN TRIBUNE ICYMI: Presidential Panel On Police Reforms Agrees To Meet All Demands By #EndSARS Protesters The Inspector-General of Police (IGP), Mohammed Adamu, has convened a meeting with stakeholders and has agreed to meet all demands raised by the #EndSARS protesters, which include halting use of force against protesters and unconditional release of arrested citizens. ICYMI: Lagos To Compensate Victims Of #EndSARS Protest With N200m ― Sanwo-Olu Lagos State governor, Mr Babajide Sanwo-Olu, has said the state government has earmarked N200million as compensation for families of victims of #EndSars protest. ICYMI: I Was A Victim Of SARS Brutality Twice, Oyo Deputy Gov Tells Protesters Oyo State deputy governor, Mr Rauf Olaniyan revealed that members of the Nigeria